For resources, the old standard is Elements of Style (which will mostly rail you on brevity). Personally, I'm a bit fan of Sound and Sense too, particularly since greentext prose is vaugely poetic. After that, the best thing you can do is read shit you like. Emulation is a huge part of writing. Don't worry about copying a style, it's virtually impossible to rip one off. Reading will help you find your voice

Anonymous Tue 03 Apr 2018 22:03:53 No.14954642 Report
Quoted By: >>14954826
>>14954536
Doesn't matter. Sound and Sense isn't about story, it's about word choice and arrangement and is directed at poetry. It's a handy guide in how to arrange words for certain inflections, such as how to generate a sense of something like urgency or melancholy using the rhythm of the language itself. Elements of Style is about actual story composition. It suggests a very dry style, but it's not a bad place to start, and offers a lot of information as to how things work under the hood.
